{"timestamp": "2025-11-29 17:09:31.365949", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nDate: (session snapshot)\n\nSummary (high level)\n- There is a clear anomaly: host host_1_1_1_1 (the 10.1.1.x access host) has no IP address / cannot reach the rest of the network, while the other access host host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.10) is functioning normally and can reach the server farm.\n- The problem localizes to the distribution router for the 10.1.1.0/24 segment (router_dist_1_1). router_dist_1_1 is not advertising or learning routes to the server networks via OSPF and therefore the 10.1.1.0/24 segment has no end-to-end reachability and cannot reach the DHCP server.\n- Root cause: router_dist_1_1 is missing the relevant OSPF network statements / OSPF advertisement for its local LAN, so OSPF adjacency/route propagation for that LAN is not occurring. As a result the distribution segment cannot reach the central server networks (including DHCP), so the host did not obtain an IP lease and is isolated.\n\nWhat I checked (tools/commands executed)\n- Full reachability/ping matrix between all hosts (get_reachability).\n- host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1 network configuration (get_host_net_config).\n- OSPF / routing state and running config on distribution routers and server-access router (frr_show_ip_route, frr_show_running_config for router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1, server_access_router, router_core_1, router_core_2).\n\nKey findings and evidence\n1) Host-level symptoms\n- host_1_1_1_1:\n  - ifconfig shows eth0 UP but no IPv4 address and no routes (no inet entry, ip_route empty).\n  - From the reachability matrix, host_1_1_1_1 pings to DHCP, DNS, web servers and other networks all fail (100% loss or unknown).\n  - Conclusion: host_1_1_1_1 has not obtained an IP (DHCP failure) and is isolated beyond the link-local layer.\n\n- host_2_1_1_1:\n  - eth0 has 10.2.1.10/24 and a default route via 10.2.1.1; pings to DHCP, DNS, load_balancer and 10.200.* web servers succeed (0% loss) with low RTTs. This segment is functioning normally.\n\n2) Distribution router (router_dist_1_1) evidence\n- router_dist_1_1 running-config shows:\n  - router ospf\n    ospf router-id 172.16.0.7\n  - — but NO network statements (no \"network 10.1.1.0/24 ...\" or similar).\n- router_dist_1_1 route table shows only connected prefixes:\n  - C>* 10.1.1.0/24 is directly connected, br0\n  - C>* 172.16.0.6/31 is directly connected, eth0\n  - There are no OSPF-learned routes for the server networks (10.200.0.0/24 etc) in router_dist_1_1's routing table.\n- Interpretation: router_dist_1_1 does not advertise its LAN into OSPF and also does not have OSPF-learned routes for remote server networks. Consequently, traffic from the 10.1.1.0/24 segment cannot be routed to the server farm or DHCP server.\n\n3) Comparison: router_dist_2_1 (10.2.1.0/24 side)\n- router_dist_2_1 running-config includes:\n  - network 10.2.1.0/24 area 1\n  - network 172.16.0.8/31 area 1\n- router_dist_2_1's route table shows OSPF routes to 10.200.0.0/24 and other inter-router links. This router is participating correctly in OSPF and its access host (host_2_1_1_1) obtained a DHCP lease and has end-to-end connectivity.\n\n4) Server-access router and core routers\n- server_access_router shows 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected and OSPF routes back to 10.2.1.0/24 via the core; core routers show OSPF routes for 10.2.1.0/24 and 10.200.0.0/24. The OSPF domain is otherwise healthy and routes are propagating between the server side and router_dist_2_1/core routers. The issue is isolated to router_dist_1_1.\n\n5) Additional observations from reachability matrix\n- host_2 and servers (10.200.*) interconnectivity is healthy.\n- Backend web VMs with addresses in 20.200.0.0/24 (the internal backend network) are intentionally separate; reachability to them from hosts may be intentionally restricted by design. The primary operational impact is on the 10.1.1.0/24 access segment, not these backend addresses.\n- Many pairs between internal servers and the load balancer/DHCP/DNS are OK, further indicating the server-side fabric is functioning.\n\nLocalization (faulty device(s) and impacted components)\n- Primary faulty device: router_dist_1_1 (distribution router for the 10.1.1.0/24 access segment).\n- Impacted devices/services:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 (no DHCP lease, no IPv4, no upstream reachability).\n  - the access switch connected to host_1_1_1_1 (switch_access_1_1_1) is implicated only insofar as it provides local L2 connectivity; it shows link up (host's interface reports RUNNING) but the problem is not at L2.\n  - Any services requiring reachability to central servers (DHCP, DNS, HTTP) from 10.1.1.0/24 are impacted.\n\nRoot-cause analysis\n- The immediate root cause is a configuration omission on router_dist_1_1: its FRR OSPF configuration contains only a router-id and no advertised network statements. Because the router is not participating/advertising its attached LAN into OSPF and does not have OSPF-learned routes for server networks, two things follow:\n  1) router_dist_1_1 cannot route or forward traffic from the 10.1.1.0/24 segment to the server farm (no route to 10.200.0.0/24), so DHCP relay/communication to the central DHCP server fails.\n  2) host_1_1_1_1 cannot obtain an address via DHCP and therefore has no IP or default route; thus it cannot reach any remote services.\n- Evidence: host_1 config shows no IP, router_dist_1_1 running-config lacks network statements, router_dist_1_1 routing table lacks OSPF-learned remote routes (whereas router_dist_2_1 and cores do have those OSPF routes).\n\nOperational impact / severity\n- High for the 10.1.1.0/24 segment: the access host(s) on that segment (host_1_1_1_1) are isolated from the enterprise services (DHCP, DNS, web services).\n- The rest of the network (server farm, load balancer, 10.2.1.0/24 segment) appears operational.\n\nNotes / other relevant points\n- The absence of an IP on host_1_1_1_1 indicates DHCP failure rather than a physical link-down (eth0 is UP and RUNNING at L2).\n- The OSPF configuration on other routers (router_dist_2_1, server_access_router, core routers) indicates the OSPF domain is functioning overall; the issue is localized to router_dist_1_1’s config.\n- Some reachability \"unknown\" or intentional failures to the 20.200.0.0/24 backend network appear consistent with the design (backend servers should not be directly accessible from hosts).\n\nNo mitigation steps are included in this report per instructions. If you want, I can next gather more targeted evidence (interface IPs on router_dist_1_1, OSPF neighbors/state, DHCP relay config on that router) or produce recommended remediation actions.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 13058, "output_tokens": 3477, "total_tokens": 16535, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 12416}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1664}}}
